<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Mackenzie, Roderick. An Account of the Athabasca Indians by a Partner of the North West Company, 1795. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0032</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">15</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">particular dwellings, but go about continually in their hunting grounds with their tents and families &#8211; they put no value on Gold and Silver; and they dress themselves in the skins of animals &#8211; they offer part of their drink to the Great Spirit &#8211; pray to the Devil &#8211; sing War songs &#8211; are given to incest &#8211; use Rackets on the Snow &#8211; make Huts under ground &#8211; fast several days when they attend the sick in order to see visions &#8211; the Women are set apart during their menses &#8211; and in mourning they tear and destroy all their effects.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Medes, Lydians, and Scythians &#8211; made incisions with their knives in their own arms and drank their own blood in commemoration of treaties.  The latter buried Men, animals, and effects with the dead &#8211; neither had any settled abode but wandered about continually from one place to another with their families &#8211; they were unacquainted with money and covered themselves with the skins of beasts.</p>

